---
import Default from '../../layouts/Default.astro';
import SectionHead from '../../components/SectionHead.astro';
import PullQuote from '../../components/PullQuote.astro';
import MetaStrip from '../../components/MetaStrip.astro';

export const meta = {
  title: "Cross-Lab Diagnosis: Why an Autonomous Research Lab Stopped Adapting",
  date: "2026-04-16",
  type: "report",
  length: "~3,000w",
  description: "Notes from observing one autonomous AI lab from inside another. Four reinforcing patterns that made a Director stop redesigning its own organization, and the five structural fixes that gave it permission to adapt again.",
};
---
<Default title="Cross-Lab Diagnosis: Why an Autonomous Research Lab Stopped Adapting · Harshith Kantamneni" description="Notes from observing one autonomous AI lab from inside another. Four reinforcing patterns that made a Director stop redesigning its own organization, and the five structural fixes that gave it permission to adapt again." current="reports">

  <div class="page-grid">
    <div class="full-bleed" style="padding: var(--space-7) var(--space-4) var(--space-3); max-width: var(--grid-max); margin: 0 auto;">
      <MetaStrip items={['REPORT', 'April 16, 2026']} />
      <h1 style="margin-top: var(--space-3); font-size: clamp(2rem, 5.5vw, 4rem); line-height: 1.05;">Cross-Lab Diagnosis: Why an Autonomous Research Lab Stopped Adapting</h1>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="page-grid">
    <div class="extended measure-tight drop-cap" style="margin-top: var(--space-5);">
      <p>
        I run two autonomous AI labs on commodity hardware. One of them, HIVE, is product-oriented and grew its agent roster organically from about ten roles to thirty-five over forty cycles. The other, AGI Lab, is research-oriented, targets a pretraining benchmark, and has stayed locked at nineteen roles for twenty-three cycles while routing two-thirds of its work to a generic agent. Both run on the same model. Both are configured with the same infrastructure. Only one of them adapts.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is what happens when you read every file in the second lab from the perspective of the first.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <SectionHead marker="SUMMARY" title="The four reinforcing patterns" />

  <div class="page-grid">
    <div class="extended measure-tight">
      <p>
        AGI Lab's organization is rigid in four ways, and the four reinforce each other.
      </p>
      <p>
        First, the runner script pre-registers a fixed roster of nineteen roles via a flag at launch. Second, the Director prompt frames that roster as closure ("nineteen roles available, use them") rather than a starting point. Third, the pre-baked prompts for each role are too generic for the Director to confidently route specific tasks to, so it falls back to a generic "general-purpose" agent for sixty-six percent of all dispatches. Fourth, no file anywhere in the lab tells the Director it is allowed to redesign the organization. Every rule it has tells it how to execute within the org. None tell it to change the org.
      </p>
      <p>
        The visible symptoms: eight of the nineteen registered roles have never been dispatched once. The Director personally reads source code, edits C files, and runs build commands in direct violation of its own "never do specialist work" rule. The PI has had to issue tactical directives to override the Director's pattern multiple times, including a four-cycle deferral of a critical optimization that the Director kept pushing forward "next cycle, next cycle, next cycle."
      </p>
      <p>
        None of this is a model failure. The Director is doing exactly what it was configured to do.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <SectionHead marker="DISPATCH" title="What the dispatch distribution shows" />

  <div class="page-grid">
    <div class="extended measure-tight">
      <p>
        Across all of AGI Lab's session logs, one hundred and sixteen agent dispatches have happened. Seventy-seven of them, sixty-six percent, went to "general-purpose," the unspecialized fallback agent. The next most-used role accounts for less than eight percent. Of the nineteen roles formally registered in the agent definitions file, eight have been dispatched zero times.
      </p>
      <p>
        Some of those dormant roles are critical. The "chief scientist" role, the top-tier research lead in the lab's own org design, has never once been launched. The "knowledge agent" role has never been launched either, despite the Director prompt stating, in capital letters, that it should run every cycle as the last agent before exit, not on demand, not optional. The Director is violating its own instructions because the existing role's pre-baked prompt does not fit what the Director actually needs done. So it reaches for "general-purpose" instead, and the dormant role stays dormant.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is the closure problem in numbers. Specialist roles exist on paper but are not callable in practice, so the Director routes around them and the specialist roles stay paper-shaped forever.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <SectionHead marker="SESSION" title="What a single session actually looks like" />

  <div class="page-grid">
    <div class="extended measure-tight">
      <p>
        I read one of AGI Lab's recent sessions line by line. Between the start and the end, the Director launched two general-purpose agents, then proceeded to read more than ten source files directly, write multiple Python tools by hand, run the build system four times in sequence, edit two C files multiple times, write a Unity test from scratch, implement a BPE tokenizer training loop personally, and poll a subprocess with bash sleep loops for nearly five minutes.
      </p>
      <p>
        The Director's own prompt says, verbatim: <em>"If you're spending more than two minutes reading source code, stop and delegate."</em> The Director spent the entire session doing specialist work.
      </p>
      <p>
        The reason is structural, not personal. The Director launched general-purpose agents for tasks like "train a BPE tokenizer" and "build a multi-file data loader" because the architecture team's baked prompt is too generic to steer toward those specifics. But general-purpose agents do not retain state or coordinate with other roles, so the Director ended up keeping the work inside its own context window and doing it personally. The CEO became the line engineer, not because it wanted to, but because the org chart did not give it anyone competent to delegate to.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <PullQuote attribution="HIVE Lab field notes">
    The CEO became the line engineer, not because it wanted to, but because the org chart did not give it anyone competent to delegate to.
  </PullQuote>

  <SectionHead marker="DIRECTIVES" title="Why the PI keeps having to intervene" />

  <div class="page-grid">
    <div class="extended measure-tight">
      <p>
        At one point AGI Lab's PI had to issue a hard directive: do not launch any experiment longer than two hundred steps until the optimization team has signed off and the GPU kernels have been optimized. The directive's preamble called out the pattern: this work had been deferred for four consecutive cycles with a new excuse every time ("fast enough at this scale," "will do next cycle," "scheduling for cycle twenty-four").
      </p>
      <p>
        That four-cycle deferral is the organizational rigidity in action. The Director could not shift resources away from experiments toward the optimization team because its org design treated "optimization team" as a consult-when-needed role rather than a first-class actor in the cycle plan. The role existed on paper but had no place in the loop, so the loop kept skipping it.
      </p>
      <p>
        Every time the PI has to step in, that is a signal the lab cannot steer itself.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <SectionHead marker="DESIGN" title="The original design called for thirty-eight roles" />

  <div class="page-grid">
    <div class="extended measure-tight">
      <p>
        Buried in the lab's design documents is the original organizational spec. It listed thirty-eight agents across four divisions. The implementation that shipped has nineteen. The design was collapsed during build-out, presumably for tractability, and once collapsed, no mechanism existed to expand it back as the actual work demanded it.
      </p>
      <p>
        HIVE's organization went the other direction. It started with about ten roles and grew to thirty-five over forty cycles, because HIVE's Director had explicit permission, and a frictionless mechanism, to evolve the roster as new kinds of work showed up. New role needed? Instantiate from a template, add five lines of specifics, run. If the role recurs, promote it to the formal roster. The friction is so low that the path of least resistance is to adapt rather than to force-fit.
      </p>
      <p>
        AGI Lab has none of that. To create a new role, the Director would have to write a sixty-line prompt from scratch, edit the agent definitions JSON, and restart the runner. The friction is high enough that the status quo always wins.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <SectionHead marker="EVALUATOR" title="No independent end-of-cycle judge" />

  <div class="page-grid">
    <div class="extended measure-tight">
      <p>
        HIVE's Director has a non-negotiable rule: launch the Evaluator agent at the end of every cycle, no exceptions. The Evaluator is an independent judge that reads the Director's pre-commitment for the cycle and evaluates whether the cycle actually met it. It catches drift before drift compounds.
      </p>
      <p>
        AGI Lab has no such mechanism. Its cycle protocol ends with "write cycle summary," which is self-evaluation. The four-cycle deferral described above was invisible to the lab itself until the PI noticed and intervened. Without an independent judge, drift compounds silently, and the only correction signal is human attention.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <SectionHead marker="ROOT" title="The root cause" />

  <div class="page-grid">
    <div class="extended measure-tight">
      <p>
        AGI Lab was designed once and frozen. The design was good for the first phase of work, where it was setting up architecture research and running the first training pass. The lab is now in a different phase, scaling up data and approaching benchmark evaluation. The work has changed. The org has not.
      </p>
      <p>
        HIVE's organization evolved because HIVE's Director was given explicit permission, and a frictionless mechanism, to evolve it. AGI Lab's Director was given neither. The fix is not to redesign the organization from outside. The fix is to give the organization the ability to redesign itself as the work requires.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <SectionHead marker="PRESCRIPTION" title="Five structural changes" />

  <div class="page-grid">
    <div class="extended measure-tight">
      <p>
        The fixes are all single-file edits. None of them break the running lab. None of them require redesigning the architecture. They are listed in priority order.
      </p>

      <h3>Change one: a PI notes file</h3>
      <p>
        Create a separate file for strategic and organizational directives, distinct from the existing tactical experiment notes. The Director reads it first every cycle, before any other state file. This is the permission slip the lab is missing. It says explicitly that the nineteen registered roles are a starting roster and not a ceiling, that the Director may invent new roles inline when the existing ones do not fit, that organizational adaptation is part of the job, and that strategic reflection is not scheduled but triggered. It also names the symptoms the Director should watch for: general-purpose dispatch above forty percent, registered agents dormant for five or more cycles, the Director personally doing specialist work for more than two minutes in a cycle. When those symptoms appear, the next cycle starts with org repair, not execution.
      </p>

      <h3>Change two: reframe the Director prompt</h3>
      <p>
        The Director prompt currently lists the agent roster as closure and treats the tactical user notes as the highest-priority input. Two small edits change this. First, the new PI notes file goes at the top of the read order, above everything else. Second, the "your agents" section gets rewritten to frame the roster as a starting point with three explicit escape hatches: launch a general-purpose agent with an inline role-specific prompt, instantiate from a template with inline additions, or promote a recurring inline role to the formal roster. The prompt is the Director's most important configuration file. Reframing it costs nothing and changes everything downstream.
      </p>

      <h3>Change three: templates for new roles</h3>
      <p>
        Add an "engineer" template and a "researcher" template under a new templates directory. Each template specifies the read list, the verification rules, the plugin set, and the workflow, with a single slot for inline specifics. New role creation drops from "write sixty lines of prompt from scratch, edit JSON, restart runner" to "instantiate template plus five lines of specifics." High friction means the status quo always wins. Low friction means the Director actually adapts.
      </p>

      <h3>Change four: an Evaluator agent</h3>
      <p>
        Add a new role to the agent definitions: an independent end-of-cycle judge that reads the Director's pre-commitment, the PI directives, the cycle log, and any code reviews, then writes a verdict. The Director cannot write a graceful session exit while an unaddressed FAIL exists. The Evaluator catches drift before drift compounds. It is the mechanism that would have caught the four-cycle deferral on cycle one rather than cycle four.
      </p>

      <h3>Change five: reframe the runner flag</h3>
      <p>
        The runner script pre-registers the roster via a CLI flag. The conservative move is to keep the flag and add a comment documenting the new framing: this is a starting roster, the Director may launch general-purpose agents with inline prompts, the Director may promote recurring inline roles to the formal roster between cycles. The bolder move is to drop the flag entirely. Try the conservative version first.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <SectionHead marker="ORDER" title="Recommended application order" />

  <div class="page-grid">
    <div class="extended measure-tight">
      <p>
        Do not try to apply all five in one cycle. The lab still has its actual research goal to pursue, and a pile of structural change all at once is its own kind of disruption.
      </p>
      <p>
        Apply changes one and two first. That is the minimum viable fix. Run for two or three cycles. Watch the dispatch distribution. If general-purpose dispatch starts dropping below forty percent and at least one previously dormant role gets called, the framing change is biting. If it does not, the diagnosis was wrong and the PI should flag it.
      </p>
      <p>
        Add change four around cycle four after the first round. The Evaluator is the enforcement mechanism, and it should land after the permission-and-framing changes have had a chance to shift behavior on their own. Add changes three and five last, around cycle six. Each change is reversible. None break the running lab.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <SectionHead marker="EXPECT" title="What to expect after applying all five" />

  <div class="page-grid">
    <div class="extended measure-tight">
      <p>
        Over the next five to ten cycles, the visible metrics should move. General-purpose dispatch should drop from sixty-six percent toward below forty. The number of dormant registered roles should drop from eight of nineteen toward two or fewer. Director specialist-work minutes per cycle should drop from roughly thirty toward less than two. The Evaluator should produce a clean verdict in most cycles, with FAIL events resolved within one cycle. New roles should appear as the work evolves, at a rate of one or more per five cycles during active phase transitions.
      </p>
      <p>
        If those metrics do not improve within ten cycles, the diagnosis was wrong and the lab should log a null result and move on. The prescription is reversible, the diagnosis is testable, and the feedback loop is short.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <SectionHead marker="ORGANIC" title="The word the PI used was 'organic'" />

  <div class="page-grid">
    <div class="extended measure-tight">
      <p>
        When AGI Lab's PI first described the problem, the framing was that the lab was not as <em>organic</em> as it was supposed to be. That word turned out to be the diagnosis. HIVE grew from ten to thirty-five roles because it was given permission to grow. AGI Lab did not grow because it was not given permission. Once you see it, every other symptom collapses into that one fact.
      </p>
      <p>
        Permission is a configuration setting. You can write it into a file.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <SectionHead marker="NOTES" title="Notes" />

  <div class="page-grid">
    <div class="extended measure-tight">
      <p><strong>Last verified</strong></p>
      <p>2026-04-16. Revisit at: ten cycles after the prescription is applied.</p>

      <p style="margin-top: var(--space-5);"><strong>Replication</strong></p>
      <p>
        Two-lab case study. Both labs run on the same model class (Claude), on similar hardware, with similar infrastructure. The diagnosis is one lab observing the other from outside. There is no independent control group.
      </p>

      <p style="margin-top: var(--space-5);"><strong>Caveats</strong></p>
      <p>
        Both labs share the same operator and the same model class. The diagnosis could be wrong. The proposed prescription is reversible, the predicted metrics are observable, and the feedback loop is short enough that a wrong diagnosis surfaces within ten cycles.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <SectionHead marker="DISCUSS" title="Discuss" />

  <div class="page-grid">
    <div class="extended measure-tight">
      <p style="font-size: var(--fs-lede); max-width: 50rem;">
        If you are running an autonomous lab and seeing similar org-rigidity patterns, I would like to hear about it. Replication attempts and counter-evidence are both welcome.
      </p>
      <div style="display: flex; gap: var(--space-4); flex-wrap: wrap; margin-top: var(--space-5);">
        <a href="mailto:kantamneniharshith@gmail.com?subject=Re%3A%20Cross-Lab%20Diagnosis" class="engagement-button">
          <span class="arrow">→</span> Reply by email
        </a>
